latestPosts.caption:
Current Summer craving inclues: Gyozas in Gochujang Garlic Sauce 🔥🥟

Cook our viral frozen gyozas first:
* Preheat a good condition non-stick pan over medium-high heat.
* Without adding oil, place twelve pieces of gyoza on the pan, flat side down.
* Slowly pour 3 oz. of water into the pan. 
*Cover and heat for about 5-7 minutes.
* Uncover and continue to pan-fry the bottom side only until golden brown and all the water has evaporated.
* Turn off heat remove gyozas from the pan and onto a plate.

Then make the sauce 👇 
* fry thinly sliced garlic cloves in oil
* 1 tablespoon of Gochugang
* 1 tablespoon Korean chili powder
* 1 teaspoon sugar
* 1/2 cup heavy cream
* 1/2 cup shredded cheese (we used romano but feel free to put your favorite creamy shredded cheese in there)
* Turn heat to simmer and mix all together

✨FINALLY✨ Gently toss the gyozas into the sauce to evenly coat and finish them off by topping sliced green onion and sesame seeds before you serve!

Have you tried the viral addictive yamitsuki cabbage recipe yet?! Its crunchy, tangy, and just so happens to pair well with crisped up gyoza 🥟✨

All you’ll need for this recipe is:
🥬 1 pound Napa cabbage (about ½ cabbage)
🥬 Kosher salt (such as Diamond Crystal) and pepper
🥬 2 medium minced garlic cloves
🥬 2 tablespoons toasted sesame oil
🥬 1 tablespoon untoasted sesame seeds

Simply slice up the cabbage and toss into a bowl and lightly salt it to help draw out excess moisture. Let the salted cabbage sit for 10 minutes and prep the sauce in the meantime.

Once the sauce is mixed, hand toss it all together to evenly coat the cabbage with the addictive garlicky sauce! Pair this with your favorite frozen gyoza and enjoy!

Meal Prepped Mie Goreng Chicken Yakisoba 🍜 FULL RECIPE BELOW 👇

Packed in glass jars, this variation on a classic Indonesian mie goreng takes only a few minutes to prepare and makes a perfect meal for lunch at the office or dinner on the go! 🍜🥗 

Ingredients
1 pkg (7 oz) Ajinomoto Vegetable Yakisoba Noodles 
2 tbsp soy sauce
2 tsp brown sugar
2 tsp sambal oelek
2 tsp sesame oil
2 tsp rice wine vinegar
1 tsp curry powder
2 cloves garlic, minced
2 cups prepared coleslaw mix
2 green onions, thinly sliced
1 cup shredded rotisserie chicken 
 
Instructions

1. Heat Vegetable Yakisoba Noodles according to package directions.

2. Meanwhile, in medium bowl, whisk together soy sauce, brown sugar, sambal oelek, sesame oil, vinegar, curry powder and garlic. Add coleslaw mix and green onions; toss to combine.

3. Divide half the noodles between two 16-oz jars, and divide half the slaw and half the chicken over the noodles. Repeat with remaining noodles, remaining slaw and remaining chicken. Garnish noodles with toasted sesame seeds, chopped cashews or sliced almonds if desired. Screw on lids. 

✨(MAKES 2 SERVINGS! Store sealed noodle jars in refrigerator for up to 2 days. Prep Time: 10 minutes / Cook Time: 5 minutes) ✨

Sizzling Garlic Chili Gyoza Dipping Oil FULL Recipe 👇 

1/2 cup neutral oil (like canola, vegetable, or avocado oil)
3 tbsp crushed red pepper flakes
2 garlic cloves, thinly sliced
1-inch piece ginger, thinly sliced
1 tbsp toasted sesame seeds
2 green onions, chopped (white parts only)
1 tsp soy sauce
1/2 tsp sugar
Salt to taste

Prepare the Aromatics ✨ Place the red pepper flakes, garlic, ginger, green onions, sesame seeds, and Sichuan peppercorns in a heatproof bowl.

Heat the Oil✨ In a small saucepan, heat the oil over medium heat until it reaches about 375°F (190°C) or until shimmering.
Test by dropping a piece of garlic in. If it sizzles immediately, it’s ready.

Pour and Infuse✨ Carefully pour the hot oil over the aromatics. It will sizzle and release a fragrant aroma.

Season and Finish✨ Stir in the soy sauce, sugar, and a pinch of salt. Let it cool for about 10 minutes.

Serve ✨Strain if desired or keep the crispy bits for extra flavor. Drizzle over your crispy-bottom gyoza for a spicy kick.
